#period function from kaggle time series course. Creates dataframe of variance values for select periods

def periods(ts, detrend='linear', ax=None):
    from scipy.signal import periodogram
    fs = pd.Timedelta(52,'W') / pd.Timedelta("1D") 
    
   
    freqencies, spectrum = periodogram( 
        ts,
        fs=fs,
        detrend=detrend,
        window="boxcar",
        scaling='spectrum',
    )
    
    df= pd.DataFrame(freqencies) 
    df['spectrum'] = spectrum
    annual = df.loc[3:6, 'spectrum'].mean()
    semi = df.loc[8:11, 'spectrum'].mean()
    quarterly = df.loc[17:20, 'spectrum'].mean()
    bimonthly = df.loc[27:29, 'spectrum'].mean()
    monthly = df.loc[54:57, 'spectrum'].mean()
    vals = (annual,semi,quarterly,bimonthly,monthly)
    return(vals)
In [17]:
# periodogram plotting fuction from Kaggle time series course. Plots period variance data from a given time series

def plot_periodogram(ts, detrend='linear', ax=None):
    from scipy.signal import periodogram
    fs = pd.Timedelta("365D") / pd.Timedelta("1D")
    freqencies, spectrum = periodogram(
        ts,
        fs=fs,
        detrend=detrend,
        window="boxcar",
        scaling='spectrum',
    )
    if ax is None:
        _, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.step(freqencies, spectrum, color="purple")
    ax.set_xscale("log")
    ax.set_xticks([1, 2, 4, 6, 12, 26, 52, 104])
    ax.set_xticklabels(
        [
            "Annual (1)",
            "Semiannual (2)",
            "Quarterly (4)",
            "Bimonthly (6)",
            "Monthly (12)",
            "Biweekly (26)",
            "Weekly (52)",
            "Semiweekly (104)",
        ],
        rotation=30,
    )
    ax.ticklabel_format(axis="y", style="sci", scilimits=(0, 0))
    ax.set_ylabel("Variance")
    ax.set_title("Periodogram")
    return ax

def make_lags(ts, lags): # creates dataframe of lag features for time series data
    return pd.concat(
        {
            f'y_lag_{i}': ts.shift(i)
        for i in range(1, lags + 1)
        },
        axis=1)

Discover optimal values for period, optimal number of lags for each family/store combination

In [26]:
per_values = [] # stores list of optimal period values
pcf_values = [] # stores list of optimal pcf values

for n in list(range(1,55)): # iterates through store numbers
    for i in cats: # iterates through family values
        frame = new.query('store_nbr == '+str(n)+' and family == '+'"'+i+'"') # creates df for each store / family combo by date

        arry = frame['sales'].droplevel([1,2]) # selects array of sales data

        vals = periods(frame['sales'].values) # creates list of period values from periods function
        if vals[-1] > .1: 
            per = 12 # checks monthly(12) period variance of sales value. if greater than .1, sets period value to 12. 
        elif vals[-2] > .1: # 
            per = 6 # checks bimonthly(6) period variance of sales value. if greater than .1, sets period value to 6. 
        elif vals[-3] > .1: # 
            per = 4 # checks quarterly(4) period variance of sales value. if greater than .1, sets period value to 4. 
        elif vals[-2] > .1: # 
            per = 2 # checks bi-annual(2) period variance of sales value. if greater than .1, sets period value to 2. 
        else:
            per = 1 # sets period value to 1 if all smaller periods below .1 
            
        pac = pacf(frame['sales'].droplevel([1,2]), nlags = 12) # creates list of values representing the partial autocorrelations of sales lags 

        # starting from end of list, iterates through values. sets pac equal to number of lags back that have partial autocorrelation greater than .1
        for i in range(1,12):
            if abs(pac[-i]) < .1:
                continue
            if abs(pac[-i]) >= .1:
                pcf = (len(pac)  - i)
                break
                
        per_values.append(per) # adds value to period list
        pcf_values.append(pcf) # adds value to pac list

predicts = [] # stores list of predicted values from training data
forecasts = [] # stores list of predicted values from test data

for n in list(range(1,55)): # iterates through store numbers
    for i in cats: # iterates through family valies
        frame = new.query('store_nbr == '+str(n)+' and family == '+'"'+i+'"') # creates dataframe of selected store number and family category

        arry = frame['sales'].droplevel([1,2]) # creates Series of sales data 

        fourier = CalendarFourier(freq="A", order=9) # creates calander fourier values

        # defines dataframe consisting of constant and trend values of timeseries, with date as the index 
        dp = DeterministicProcess(
        index=total_sales.index,
        constant=True,               
        order=2,                     
        seasonal=True,               
        additional_terms=[fourier],  
        drop=True,
        )

        X = dp.in_sample() # creates deterministic dataframe for dates in index

        X2 = make_lags(arry, lags=12) # creates lag features for sales values
        X2 = X2.fillna(0.0) # fills null values with 0.0

        X3 = pd.merge(X,X2, left_on = X.index, right_on = X2.index) # combine dp and lag dataframes
        X3 = X3.set_index('key_0') # sets id as index

        y = arry[:] # creates copy of sales values by date (y)

        X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X3, y, test_size=60, shuffle=False) # splits data into train, test datasets

        # Fit and predict
        model = LinearRegression() # defines linear regression model
        model.fit(X_train, y_train) # fits model to training data.


        y_pred = pd.DataFrame(model.predict(X_train), index=pd.to_datetime(y_train.index, errors ='ignore')) # creates dataframe of predictions from training data
        y_fore = pd.DataFrame(model.predict(X_test), index=pd.to_datetime(y_test.index, errors = 'ignore')) # creates dataframe of predictions from testing data

       
        predicts.append(y_pred) # appends training data predictions to full list

    for idx, item in enumerate(cats): # iterates through family values

        frame = frame.set_index('id') # sets date column as the dataframe index

        arry = frame['scaled_residuals'] # creates Series of scaled residual values

        lags = make_lags(arry, lags=12) # creates 12 lag variables from scaled residuals

        df_lags = pd.concat([df_lags,lags]) # appends store / family lag data to lag dataframe

data = data.merge(df_lags, how='left', left_index=True,  right_index=True) # adds lag data to features dataframe
test_train = train.merge(df_lags, how='left', left_index=True,  right_index=True) # adds lag data to train dataframe
test_test = test.merge(df_lags, how='left', left_index=True,  right_index=True) # adds lag data to test dataframe

def pipe(data): # creates function to transform data to correct format for XGBoost
    data['scaled_residuals'] = stand_scaler.transform(data['resid'].values.reshape(-1,1)) # adds scaled residuals to dataframe (Y value)

    data[['onpromotion','dow','month','dcoilwtico','percip','max_temp']] = max_scaler.transform(data[['onpromotion','dow','month','dcoilwtico','percip','max_temp']]) # scales appropriate columns using min/max scaler

    data = data.drop(['date','id'], axis=1) # drops date and id columns
    
    # remove scaled residuals column and replace at front of dataframe. XGBoost requires y value to be first column
    resids = data['scaled_residuals']
    data.drop(labels=['scaled_residuals'], axis=1,inplace = True)
    data.insert(0, 'scaled_residuals', resids)

    data = data.dropna() # removes null value rows from dataframe
    data = pd.get_dummies(data, columns = ['store_nbr','dow','month','family',], dtype='float32') # creates dummy variables (0 or 1) for appropriate columns 

    return(data) # returns new dataframe

# creates function that reformats our input data to be sent to model for predictions
def predictionator_2(data, rows=1000): 
    split_array = np.array_split(data, int(data.shape[0] / float(rows) + 1)) # splits data into chunks to be more easily processed
    predictions = "" # creates empty string to store predicted values
    for array in split_array: 
        predictions = "".join([predictions, predictor.predict(array).decode("utf-8")]) # appends predicted values to 'predictions'

    return predictions.split("\n")[:-1] # returns list of predicted values

    temp = forcasting[forcasting['date'] == item] # creates dataframe of predicting info for selected date

    data = pd.concat([tail_2, temp]) # appends temp to dataframe


    for n in list(range(1,55)): # iterates through store numbers
        for idx2, item2 in enumerate(cats): # iterates through family values
            frame = data.query('store_nbr == '+str(n)+' and family == '+'"'+item2+'"') # creates dataframe of data from selected store / family

            frame = frame.set_index('id') # sets id column as the dataframe index

            arry = frame['scaled_residuals'] # creates Series of scaled residual values

            lags = make_lags(arry, lags=12) # creates 12 lag variables from scaled residuals

            df_lags = pd.concat([df_lags,lags]) # appends store / family lag data to lag dataframe


    data[['onpromotion','dow','month','dcoilwtico','percip','max_temp']] = max_scaler.transform(data[['onpromotion','dow','month','dcoilwtico','percip','max_temp']]) # scales appropriate columns using min/max scaler

    data = pd.get_dummies(data, columns = ['store_nbr','dow','month','family',], dtype='float32') # creates dummy variables (0 or 1) for appropriate columns 

    plus = data.merge(df_lags, how='left', left_index=True,  right_index=True) # adds lag data to features dataframe

    plus_16 = plus[plus['date'] == item] # singles out date we are predicting

    plus_16 = plus_16.drop(['scaled_residuals','resid'], axis=1) # drops un-necessary columns

    col_list = X_test.drop('scaled_residuals', axis=1).columns # list of columns in correct order for prediction

    plus_16 = plus_16[col_list] # rearranges our dataframe into correct order for prediction

    predictions = predictionator_2(plus_16.to_numpy()[:,:]) # predicts scaled residuals

    new_tail = forcasting[forcasting['date'] == item] # collects data to be appended to original dataset

    new_tail['scaled_residuals'] = predictions # adds newly predicted values to data

    tail_2 = pd.concat([tail_2, new_tail]) # appends data to end of original dataset for next date's predicting

Because our seasonal and trend predictions also include lag variables, we can either predict and append day by day like we did with our residuals or create a multi-step prediction with linear regression to predict X amount of days past our timeseries. For this project we will use multi-step.

In [169]:
# creates function to predict multiple future values
def make_multistep_target(ts, steps):
    return pd.concat(
        {f'y_step_{i + 1}': ts.shift(-i)
         for i in range(steps)},
        axis=1)

for n in list(range(1,55)): # iterates through store numbers
    for i in cats: # iterates through family valies
        frame = new2.query('store_nbr == '+str(n)+' and family == '+'"'+i+'"') # create dataframe of selected store number and family category

        if np.sum(frame['sales'].values) == 0: # skips dataframes with no sales
            continue

        arry = frame['sales'].droplevel([1,2]) # creates Series of sales data 
        '''
        for j in list(arry.index):
            if arry[j] < 0.01:
                arry = arry.drop(j)
            else:
                break
        '''


        fourier = CalendarFourier(freq="A", order=12) # creates calendar fourier values

        # defines dataframe consisting of constant and trend values of timeseries, with date as the index 
        dp = DeterministicProcess(
        index=frame.index.get_level_values(0),
        constant=True,               
        order=2,                     
        seasonal=True,               
        additional_terms=[fourier],  
        drop=True,
        )

        X = dp.in_sample() # creates deterministic dataframe for dates in index


        X2 = make_lags(arry, lags=9) # creates lag features for sales values
        X2 = X2.fillna(0.0) # fills null values with 0.0

        X3 = pd.merge(X,X2, left_on = X.index, right_on = X2.index) # combine dp and lag dataframes
        X3 = X3.set_index('key_0') # sets id as index

        y = arry[:] # creates copy of sales values by date (y)

        y = make_multistep_target(y, steps=16).dropna() # creates multistep target for sales values
        y, X5 = y.align(X3, join='inner', axis=0) # realigns X,y for model fitting


        # Fit and predict
        model = LinearRegression() 
        model.fit(X5, y) # fits model to data
        
        y_pred = pd.DataFrame(model.predict(X3), index=frame.index.get_level_values(0), columns = y.columns) # creates dataframe of predicted multistep values
        y_pred['store_nbr'] = n # adds store number to prediction dataframe
        y_pred['family'] = i # adds family name to prediction dataframe
        dates_pred.loc[len(dates_pred)] = y_pred.iloc[-1].values # appends relevant predicted values to dates_pred dataframe
